01":"1201","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Quartermain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Quarterman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Quarterman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Germaine, Marcel, Pascal.","English (Oxfordshire and Surrey): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>quatre mayns</i>, <i>quatre mans</i> ‘four hands’, which has been taken to imply ‘mail-fisted’ but was perhaps used of a skilled craftsman or a dextrous juggler or conjuror."]}]},{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Herbert Quartermain was born in 1180, in North Weston, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Herbert Quartermain, was 11177 and his mother, Lecia Knyvet, was 21. He had at least 2 sons with Lecia Knyvett. He died in 1250, in North Weston, Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1180–1250":"1180–1250","1226–Male":"1226–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1230–1285":"1230–1285","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1160–1201":"1160–1201","Aft 1201":"pärast 1201","Bef September 1201":"enne septembrit 1201","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1180